    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey my bathroom sink is dripping constantly and i cant figure out why. it's a regular old handle faucet, not one of those single lever ones. what kind of tools do i need to fix it and how do i actually replace the washer to stop the leaking?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You need a pair of **gloved hands** (or at least a towel to catch the water) and a **screwdriver** (specifically a flathead, which is the most common for bathroom faucets). You also need a **new washer**, which you can buy at any hardware store, or even a **globe** if you want to keep the old one for a bit longer.\n\nFirst, you need to loosen the **handle** so you can turn the **valve** underneath. If you don't loosen the handle, the valve is stuck, and the washer won't come out. Once the handle is off, you'll see the **valve** and the **washer** sitting there. The washer is the little rubber ring that holds the water in place; if it's worn out, water will leak out.\n\nTo replace it, you need to **unscrew the valve** (which is usually a quarter-turn counter-clockwise) and then **remove the old washer** by twisting it off. You can do this by hand, but if it's stuck, you might need a **gloved hand** to help turn it. Once the washer is off, you can **install a",
      "source": "target",
